>c</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sup" style="font-size: 83.3%; vertical-align: 0.347em; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0.06em;"><span class="mjx-mn" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">2</span></span></span></span></span><span style="border-bottom: 1.3px solid; top: -0.296em; width: 0.809em;" class="mjx-line"></span></span><span style="height: 1.702em; vertical-align: -0.601em;" class="mjx-vsize"></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="border-bottom: 1.3px solid; top: -0.296em; width: 3.971em;" class="mjx-line"></span></span><span style="height: 3.095em; vertical-align: -1.95em;" class="mjx-vsize"></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fn4w4wnw6odfq"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnref4w4wnw6odfq">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> One prior guess I have seen is Eliezer Yudkowsky suggested that human level AGI could be done on a 286 (if the programmer is a superintelligent AGI) or a &quot;home computer from 1995&quot; (maybe a 90 Mhz Pentium, if the programmer is a human) <a href="https://intelligence.org/2022/03/01/ngo-and-yudkowsky-on-scientific-reasoning-and-pivotal-acts/">https://intelligence.org/2022/03/01/ngo-and-yudkowsky-on-scientific-reasoning-and-pivotal-acts/</a></p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnai4pdbcrhfo"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefai4pdbcrhfo">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> <a href="https://www.mit.edu/~ecprice/wordlist.10000">https://www.mit.edu/~ecprice/wordlist.10000</a> for example is 75880 bytes. As well word vectors usually have vector length of at least 100, so those would not even fit a 1000 basic words with the vectors. See for example GloVe: &quot;Global Vectors for Word Representation&#39;&#39; <a href="https://aclanthology.org/D14-1162/">https://aclanthology.org/D14-1162/</a> for discussion on word vector size.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnl1a8ho68hof"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefl1a8ho68hof">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> So basically, I think it is highly likely that AGIT(Risc-V 64G or similar, x, 25 kFLOPS, 64 KiB) = False for all x.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnt347c6jutbr"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnreft347c6jutbr">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Wikipedia lists this and cites Ray Kurtzweil. Note that until we have actually done this, this is a bit of a conjecture. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_performance_by_orders_of_magnitude">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_performance_by_orders_of_magnitude</a> Ray Kurtzweil in &quot;The Age of Spiritual Machines&#39;&#39;, page 103, gives the following calculation: 100 trillion connections * 200 calculations per second = <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="20*10^{15}"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mn"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">20</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo MJXc-space2"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">∗</span></span> <span class="mjx-msubsup MJXc-space2"><span class="mjx-base"><span class="mjx-mn"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">10</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sup" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: 0.591em; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-texatom" style=""><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mn"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">15</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> calculations per second, and he comments that this might be a high estimate.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnx0ps7qqw5q9"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefx0ps7qqw5q9">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> So basically, I think it is likely that AGIT(Top 10 computer in 2023, 1 year, 60 petaflops, 1000 TiB) = True.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnob9an78pbkp"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefob9an78pbkp">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Mentioned in the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Codd%27s_cellular_automaton">wikipedia article</a> and see <a href="https://sourceforge.net/p/golly/code/ci/master/tree/Patterns/Self-Rep/Devore/Devore-body.rle">https://sourceforge.net/p/golly/code/ci/master/tree/Patterns/Self-Rep/Devore/Devore-body.rle</a> for the code.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnfuqqjhtkkfd"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnreffuqqjhtkkfd">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drosophila_connectome">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drosophila_connectome</a> and <a href="https://flywire.ai/">https://flywire.ai/</a></p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnt3nv8x4807"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnreft3nv8x4807">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> LaMDA: Language Models for Dialog Applications, section 10 <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2201.08239">https://arxiv.org/abs/2201.08239</a></p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fne1cu9j87dlu"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefe1cu9j87dlu">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Basically, LLMs are showing signs of general intelligence.  Examples of an evaluation of GPT-4 are listed in &quot;Sparks of Artificial General Intelligence: Early experiments with GPT-4&#39;&#39; <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.12712">https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.12712</a></p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fngqbwgzo38ql"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefgqbwgzo38ql">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> LaMDA&#39;s largest model has 137 billion parameters, 137 G*4 B/24 GB = 22.8, assuming 32 bit floats, but lower precision could probably be used.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fn4mfh2asjh9f"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnref4mfh2asjh9f">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Running a LLMs on regular computers including a RaspberryPi: <a href="https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2023/03/you-can-now-run-a-gpt-3-level-ai-model-on-your-laptop-phone-and-raspberry-pi/">https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2023/03/you-can-now-run-a-gpt-3-level-ai-model-on-your-laptop-phone-and-raspberry-pi/</a></p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fno6lpelrh4v"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefo6lpelrh4v">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Eliezer Yudkowsky has suggested shutting down large GPU clusters and then keep lowering the limit in several places, most notably in:<br> <a href="https://intelligence.org/2023/04/07/pausing-ai-developments-isnt-enough-we-need-to-shut-it-all-down/">https://intelligence.org/2023/04/07/pausing-ai-developments-isnt-enough-we-need-to-shut-it-all-down/</a></p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnfq04uggh3yh"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnreffq04uggh3yh">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM_Syste