 &#39;Frequentism&#39; as definitely believing in probabilities - just probabilities of drawing different samples, rather than a priori probabilities, or probabilities of ground truths given a sample. So I feel that the question is which type of probability is more important, or more relevant. (Like, I certainly agree that &quot;understand what sort of algorithms do well in probabilistic settings&quot; is the right way to think about cognition, and you don&#39;t have to over-reify the features of those cognitive algorithms!)</p><section class="dialogue-message-header CommentUserName-author UsersNameDisplay-noColor"> DanielFilan </section></section><section class="dialogue-message ContentStyles-debateResponseBody" message-id="DgsGzjyBXN8XSK22q-Sun, 15 Oct 2023 20:17:30 GMT" user-id="DgsGzjyBXN8XSK22q" display-name="DanielFilan" submitted-date="Sun, 15 Oct 2023 20:17:30 GMT" user-order="1"><p> Another potential question could be &quot;how valuable is it for cognitive algorithms to not be constrained by having their main internal representations be probability distributions over possible worlds&quot;.</p><section class="dialogue-message-header CommentUserName-author UsersNameDisplay-noColor"> DanielFilan </section></section><section class="dialogue-message ContentStyles-debateResponseBody" message-id="DgsGzjyBXN8XSK22q-Sun, 15 Oct 2023 20:17:52 GMT" user-id="DgsGzjyBXN8XSK22q" display-name="DanielFilan" submitted-date="Sun, 15 Oct 2023 20:17:52 GMT" user-order="1"><p> Basically you presented this as a hot take, and I&#39;m trying to figure out where you expect to disagree with people.</p><section class="dialogue-message-header CommentUserName-author UsersNameDisplay-noColor"> DanielFilan </section></section><section class="dialogue-message ContentStyles-debateResponseBody" message-id="DgsGzjyBXN8XSK22q-Sun, 15 Oct 2023 20:18:13 GMT" user-id="DgsGzjyBXN8XSK22q" display-name="DanielFilan" submitted-date="Sun, 15 Oct 2023 20:18:13 GMT" user-order="1"><p> Another possible 